description: Deterministic Logarithmic-space is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine, using only a logarithmic amount of writable memory space.
Nondeterministic Logarithmic-space is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a nondeterministic Turing machine, using only a logarithmic amount of writable memory space.
Deterministic Polynomial Time is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine in a polyomial amount of computation time.

Bounded-error Probabilistic Polynomial Time is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a probalistic Turing machine with two-sided error in a polyomial amount of computation time.
Zero-error Probabilistic Polynomial Time is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a probalistic Turing machine without error in a polyomial amount of computation time.

Randomized Probabilistic Polynomial Time is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a probalistic Turing machine with 1-sided bounded error in a polyomial amount of computation time.

Nodeterministic Polynomial Time is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a nondeterministic Turing machine in a polyomial amount of computation time. It is also defined as the complexity class of decision problems that can be verified by a deterministic Turing machine in a polynomial amount of computation time.
Deterministic Polynomial-space is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine, using only a polynomial amount of writable memory space.
Deterministic Exponential Time is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine in an exponential amount of computation time.
Nondeterministic Exponential Time is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a nondeterministic Turing machine in an exponential amount of computation time.
Deterministic Exponential-space is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine, using only an exponential amount of writable memory space.
Nondeterministic Exponential-space is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a nondeterministic Turing machine, using only an exponential amount of writable memory space.
Nick's Class is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a parallel computer with a polynomial number of processors in a polylogarithmic amount of computation time.
NC^1 is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a parallel computer with a polynomial number of processors in a O(log n) amount of computation time.

L/poly is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine, using only an logarithmic amount of writable memory space and with advice strings of polynomial length.
P/poly is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a deterministic Turing machine in a polynomial amount of time with advice strings of polynomial length.
P/poly is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a nondeterministic Turing machine in a polynomial amount of time with advice strings of polynomial length.

Bounded-error Probabilistic Logarithmic-space is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a probalistic Turing machine with two-sided error, using only an logarithmic amount of writable memory space.

Randomized Logarithmic-space is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a probalistic Turing machine with 1-sided error, using only an logarithmic amount of writable memory space.

Probabilistic Logarithmic-space  is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a probalistic Turing machine with unbounded error, using only an logarithmic amount of writable memory space.
Probabilistic Polynomial Time is the complexity class of decision problems that can be solved by a probalistic Turing machine with unbounded error  in a polynomial amount of time.
